    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm struggling with scope creep in my current software project. stakeholders keep asking for \"small tweaks\" mid-sprint and it's ruining our velocity. any professional ways to handle this or stop it from happening?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Scope creep can be a real challenge in software development. You can't let the stakeholders' requests get out of hand, or it'll be like trying to herd a pack of wild rabbits - they'll keep changing direction and slowing you down. \n\nTo tackle this, you can try setting clear boundaries and expectations with your stakeholders. Explain that \"small tweaks\" can quickly add up and impact the overall project timeline and budget. You can also establish a formal change management process, like a \"change request form\" or a \"stakeholder approval process,\" to ensure that all changes are properly documented and approved before they're implemented. This will help you keep the project on track and prevent scope creep from becoming a major issue. \n\nAnother approach is to use a \"stoplight\" system, where you categorize each request as green (approved), yellow (pending), or red (not approved). This will give you a clear visual representation of the requests and help you prioritize the ones that are most important. \n\nIt's also essential to communicate the impact of scope creep to your stakeholders and explain how it can affect the project's overall success. You can use a \"scope creep impact analysis\" to help them understand the potential consequences of their requests. This will",
      "source": "target",
