      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Those tiny, annoying little bits of work can be a real challenge to manage. It's like trying to catch a swarm of tiny, pesky insects with a net - they're everywhere and can be hard to track.\n\nOne approach is to use a \"parking lot\" for these small requests. This is a centralized location where you can temporarily store requests that don't fit into the current sprint or project plan. When the parking lot is full, you can review the requests and prioritize them for future sprints or projects. This will help you keep the requests from piling up and make it easier to manage them.\n\nAnother technique is to use a \"request filter\" - a set of criteria that you use to evaluate incoming requests and determine whether they fit into the current project plan. For example, you might have a filter that says \"requests that require more than 2 hours of work\" or \"requests that are not critical to the project's success.\" By applying these filters, you can help ensure that only the most important requests make it into the project plan.\n\nIt's also essential to remember that, as a developer, you have a responsibility to say \"no\" to requests that don't fit into the project plan. This can be a",
